  hook:"Every time you flip a light switch, charge your phone, or turn on a fan — you're commanding the movement of trillions of electrons through copper wires at nearly the speed of light. India's power grid — the world's third largest — generates over 400 GW of capacity, powering 1.4 billion people across 6 million kilometers of transmission lines. A single lightning bolt carries 1 billion joules of energy at 300 million volts. Your wall socket delivers a carefully regulated 220 volts at exactly 50 cycles per second. From the massive turbines of a thermal power station to the tiny electrons flowing through your phone's processor, electricity is the invisible force that powers every aspect of modern civilization. But what IS electricity, really?",
